    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-09-05T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-09-05T08:00:00-05:00" n="666"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d666">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">124.613/983: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="#p_SLA1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-09-05T16:00:00+03:00"
                            >September 5, 1939—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 4:02 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>507. The Soviet employees of the Embassy are apprehensive of the effect of the
                    war on the internal situation in the Soviet Union and the consequence of such
                    effect on them in that they have already had evidence that [for?] all Soviet
                    nationals closely associated with foreigners it will involve more
                    [surveillance?] than heretofore by their Government. The first concrete result
                    of such apprehension is the resignation effective in 1 month of Victor Sniffer,
                    senior translator and the most valuable research worker in the Mission. Three
                    other translators, in addition to some of the chauffeurs, messengers, and other
                    minor employees now assert increasing dissatisfaction with the Embassy’s failure
                    to obtain salary adjustments for them effective July 1 (see <pb facs="0961"
                        n="855" xml:id="pg_855"/> Embassy’s despatch No. 2034 of January 22 this
                        year<note n="57" xml:id="d666fn57">Not printed.</note>) and their
                    dissatisfaction with the compensation received by them when coupled with their
                    apprehension creates the possibility that they will terminate their services as
                    soon as employment outside the Embassy becomes available.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SLA1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
